Transmissible spongiform encephalopathies encompass a group of neurodegenerative diseases including scrapie in sheep, bovine spongiform encephalopathy in cattle, and human pathologies such as Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease and Gerstmann-Straussler-Scheinker syndrome (1 to 3). The principal agent thought to be responsible for the transmission of these diseases is the infectious form of the prion protein (PrP)
